Microtasks (Promise callbacks, queueMicrotask, MutationObserver) execute after each macrotask and before the next UI render. Macrotasks (setTimeout, setInterval, I/O tasks) execute in the next iteration of the event loop. This means Promise .then() callbacks always execute before any setTimeout callbacks, even if the setTimeout delay is 0ms. <strong>Example:</strong><br/><br/><pre><code>console.log('1');
setTimeout(() => console.log('2'), 0);
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('3'));
console.log('4');
// Output: 1, 4, 3, 2</code></pre>

The async function will continue executing immediately without waiting for the Promise to settle. The Promise will still execute (it's already started), but you lose the ability to catch its rejection or use its resolved value. The async function will return a Promise that resolves with whatever comes after the un-awaited Promise. <strong>Example:</strong><br/><br/><pre><code>async function example() {
  Promise.reject('error'); // Unhandled rejection!
  return 'done';
}
example().then(console.log); // logs 'done' immediately</code></pre>

Wrap the callback call inside a new Promise constructor. In the executor function, call the async API and resolve/reject the Promise based on the callback's results. <strong>Example:</strong><br/><br/><pre><code>function readFilePromise(path) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    fs.readFile(path, 'utf8', (err, data) => {
      if (err) reject(err);
      else resolve(data);
    });
  });
}
// Usage:
const content = await readFilePromise('/path/to/file.txt');</code></pre>

The antipattern is wrapping a Promise-returning function inside a new Promise when you already have a Promise. <strong>Bad (antipattern):</strong><br/><br/><pre><code>return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  fetch(url).then(resolve).catch(reject);
});</code></pre><br/><strong>Good:</strong><br/><br/><pre><code>return fetch(url);</code></pre><br/>The antipattern adds unnecessary nesting, loses error handling, and can cause unhandled rejections or memory leaks.

In Promise chains, errors propagate through the chain until they hit a .catch(). If no .catch() exists, the rejection becomes an unhandled rejection. In async/await, errors propagate via try/catch. If no try/catch is present, the async function returns a rejected Promise. Both mechanisms are equivalent -- async/await is just more readable. <strong>Promise chain:</strong><br/><br/><pre><code>fetch(url)
  .then(res => res.json())
  .then(data => process(data))
  .catch(err => console.error(err));</code></pre><br/><strong>Async/await:</strong><br/><br/><pre><code>try {
  const res = await fetch(url);
  const data = await res.json();
  await process(data);
} catch (err) {
  console.error(err);
}</code></pre>

Promise.race() returns a Promise that settles (fulfills or rejects) as soon as the first input Promise settles. Use it for timeouts: <br/><br/><pre><code>function withTimeout(promise, ms) {
  const timeout = new Promise((_, reject) =>
    setTimeout(() => reject(new Error('Timeout')), ms)
  );
  return Promise.race([promise, timeout]);
}

try {
  const data = await withTimeout(fetch(url), 5000);
} catch (err) {
  console.log('Request timed out or failed');
}</code></pre>

In async/await, you use try/catch blocks. However, if you need to handle errors from a specific await statement differently, you can combine both approaches: <br/><br/><pre><code>async function handleMultiple() {
  const result1 = await task1().catch(err => ({ error: err }));
  if (result1.error) { /* handle task1 error */ }

  try {
    const result2 = await task2();
    // process result2
  } catch (err) {
    // handle task2 error
  }
}</code></pre><br/>The choice depends on granularity needed -- per-call error handling vs. batch error handling.

Promise.resolve(value) returns a Promise that is resolved with the given value. If the value is already a Promise, it returns that Promise. If it's a thenable (an object with .then), it unwraps it. If it's a plain value, it wraps it in a fulfilled Promise. <strong>Use cases:</strong> (1) Converting a value to a Promise for uniform async handling. (2) Starting a Promise chain synchronously. (3) In async function polyfills. <strong>Example:</strong><br/><br/><pre><code>// Normalize: function might return value or Promise
function getUser(id) {
  if (cache[id]) return Promise.resolve(cache[id]);
  return fetchUserFromAPI(id);
}</code></pre>

